{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17611679","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17611679"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:13:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:13:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16235"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16235","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16235"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.09,0,0.69,0.23]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8926"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67325"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8926","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8926"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16235"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52777"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7017"},{"type":"tags","id":"7662"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"},{"type":"tags","id":"10646"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21243"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21246"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22546"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67325","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67325"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman has a breast biopsy performed. The histological image shows infiltrating malignant cells arranged in irregular glands with surrounding desmoplastic stroma (Image). The gross specimen demonstrates a firm, irregular mass with stellate borders.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Fibroadenoma","Medullary carcinoma","Paget\u0027s disease of the nipple","Invasive ductal carcinoma","Invasive lobular carcinoma"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe features shown are classic for \u003Cstrong\u003Einvasive ductal carcinoma,\u003C/strong\u003E which is characterised by irregular infiltrating glands, nuclear pleomorphism, and desmoplastic stromal reaction. This is the most common type of breast cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options can be excluded based on their distinctive features:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFibroadenoma\u003C/strong\u003E typically shows well-circumscribed borders and biphasic proliferation of epithelial and stromal components.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMedullary carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E demonstrates a syncytial growth pattern with prominent lymphocytic infiltrate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPaget\u0027s disease of the nipple\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by eczematous changes of the nipple and areola, often associated with underlying ductal carcinoma in situ or invasive carcinoma, but not by the described histological features.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInvasive lobular carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E typically shows a single-file pattern of tumour cells with minimal desmoplastic response.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe gross appearance of a firm, irregular mass with stellate borders is also typical of invasive ductal carcinoma.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Invasive ductal carcinoma is the most common type of breast cancer, accounting for 70-80% of cases.","Key histological features of invasive ductal carcinoma include irregular glands, nuclear pleomorphism, and desmoplastic stromal reaction.","Invasive ductal carcinoma typically presents as a firm, irregular mass that may cause skin or nipple retraction."],"references":["\u0022Histopathology of mucinous invasive ductal carcinoma of the breast\u0022 by Mikael H\u00e4ggstr\u00f6m is licensed under Creative Commons Attribution-Share Alike 1.0 license. https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Histopathology_of_mucinous_invasive_ductal_carcinoma_of_the_breast.jpg","Wang J, Li B, Luo M, Huang J, Zhang K, Zheng S, Zhang S, Zhou J. Progression from ductal carcinoma in situ to invasive breast cancer: molecular features and clinical significance. Signal Transduct Target Ther. 2024 Apr 3;9(1):83. doi: 10.1038/s41392-024-01779-3. PMID: 38570490; PMCID: PMC10991592.","Zangouri V MD, Akrami M MD, Tahmasebi S MD, Talei A MD, Ghaeini Hesarooeih A MD. Medullary Breast Carcinoma and Invasive Ductal Carcinoma: A Review Study. Iran J Med Sci. 2018 Jul;43(4):365-371. PMID: 30046204; PMCID: PMC6055214.","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52777"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16235"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21223"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21223","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21223"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/4N8qDskoNHL0oEtUMCVfeaIXsJXZFB.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/4N8qDskoNHL0oEtUMCVfeaIXsJXZFB.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":1073}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52777","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52777"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-04T21:11:45+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-04T21:12:31+10:30"},"relationships":{"it